text:
That bill has been rapidly gaining cosponsors in the past few days, including the support of Parkland’s Congressman @RepTedDeutch, who spoke about the measure in the televised town hall in Parkland, as well as our first Republican cosposponsors.

More on this later today! #GVRO

The Gun Violence Restraining Order Act, which @RepCarbajal, @RepEsty and I introduced in the House last year, along with @SenFeinstein’s Senate companion, is the only bill in Congress that would create a framework for states to adopt such laws, and give them incentives to do so.

These laws give families and law enforcement tools to get guns out of the hands of people who are a threat to themselves of others.

GVRO/ERPO laws also come with ample due process protections for gun owners, which is why they have drawn widespread support from conservatives.

Today on @nytimes’ The Daily, @mikiebarb explored laws to create what we call “gun violence restraining orders” or “extreme risk protection orders,” also known as “red flag” laws.

Many states are considering them, but there is only one bill in Congress: our #GVRO Act.

text:
2 years ago Congress voted to reform the Toxic Substances Control Act to strengthen safety regulations on potentially dangerous chemicals. 

To say it was bipartisan is an understatement: the final vote was 403-12.

It wasn't perfect, but it was a step forward. 4/

Problems with TSCA came to a head in recent years and got major public attention when dangerous chemical spills in West Virginia, North Carolina, and elsewhere caused public health crises affecting thousands of people.

Then Congress began the long process of updating the law. 3/

The landmark regulation of chemicals was called the Toxic Substances Control Act, passed by Congress in 1976. But it was not updated as the years passed, and big gaps in chemical regulations became more apparent over time. 2/
